A list of 'significant viral diseases of camelids' is presented on OIE's website at http://www.oie.int/our-scientific-expertise/specific-information-and-recommendations/camelidae-diseases/. They are divided into 3 groups:
Group I = "known to produce significant diseases": camelpox, contagious ecthyma, papillomatosis, rabies, RVF [Rift Valley fever];
Group II = "diseases for which camelids are potential pathogen carriers": African horse sickness, bluetongue, BVD [bovine viral diarrhea], PPR;
Group III = "minor diseases": CCHF [Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever], herpesvirus infections (EHV, IBR [Infectious bovine rhinotracheitis]), West Nile fever.

Detailed background of the said information, as compiled by OIE's ad-hoc group for camelid diseases in 2010, is available at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Our_scientific_expertise/docs/pdf/A_Diseases_Camelids_May10.pdf.

In view of the recent report from Iran and an earlier report from Sudan (see reference 2, below) describing a serious clinical disease caused by PPR virus in dromedary camels, the place (group) of PPR within OIE's list may deserve reconsideration. OIE is holding during the current week its 84th annual General Session in Paris.

Recently, an undiagnosed lethal disease of dromedary camels has been reported from Pakistan, Iran's eastern neighbor and a country the camel population of which ranks 6th globally. PPR has been one of the main suspects, requested information pending (see 20160521.4237105).

References
----------
1. Abraham G and Berhan A: The use of antigen-capture enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) for the diagnosis of rinderpest and peste des petits ruminants in ethiopia. Trop Anim Health Prod. 200; 33(5):423-30; abstract available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11556621.
2. Khalafalla AI, Saeed IK, Ali YH, Abdurrahman MB, et al: An outbreak of peste des petits ruminants (PPR) in camels in the Sudan. Acta Trop. 2010; 116(2): 161-5. doi: 10.1016/j.actatropica.2010.08.002; abstract available at http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0001706X10002044.
